<HEADLINE>
<P>
VANISHING VINYL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
You can't stop progress, and I do admit that compact discs can sound pretty 
wonderful . . . but surely there is a place for the vinyl record. 
</P>
<P>
I know I am not alone when I ask that the record companies not give up on a 
format that has been pretty good to them for nearly 45 years. 
</P>
<P>
I get an empty feeling when I think that vinyl albums are almost obsolete; I 
feel like I'm losing a long-time friend. For me, LP albums are like old 
baseball cards: There is a sense of history behind every one of them. 
</P>
<P>
CDs and cassettes are now the desired formats in the music industry. It won't 
be long before only a few of us Neanderthals are left with only a turntable and 
our memories of more innocent days. 
</P>
<P>
MARC PLATT 
</P>
<P>
Culver City 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
